  "notes": "Standard Danish (rigsdansk). QUANTITY: a stressed vowel is long in an open syllable / before a single consonant and short before a consonant cluster or a doubled consonant letter; Danish itself has NO long consonants, so doubled letters are read as a single consonant (they only signal the preceding short vowel). This is encoded with data only: doubled letters are grapheme keys mapping to a length-marked consonant (⟨bb⟩→/bː/), consonant clusters are grapheme keys mapping to the concatenated phonemes (⟨st⟩→/sd/), the vowel-shortening allophone rules fire on `followed_by_phoneme` = those cluster/geminate phonemes, and a second set of rules degeminates /Cː/→/C/. SCHWA: unstressed ⟨e⟩ is [ə] (Grønnum 2005; Basbøll 2005) — the single most frequent segment in the language. SOFT D: /d/ after a vowel is the approximant [ð] (mad [mað], gade [ɡæːðə]). SILENT D: ⟨nd⟩→[n], ⟨ld⟩→[l], ⟨rd⟩→[ʁ]. NO ASPIRATION AFTER /s/: ⟨sp st sk⟩ → [sb sd sɡ]. R: onset ⟨r⟩ is the uvular [ʁ]; coda r-vocalisation ([ɐ̯]) is NOT encoded. STØD is suprasegmental and is not encoded; the WikiPron/Wiktionary gold marks it (ˀ) and also writes /r/ as ⟨r⟩ rather than ⟨ʁ⟩ — both are transcription-convention differences from this spec, not errors in it.",
  "quality": "research",
